items.title: Pterostylis melagramma
items.content_text: Please help with ID and sorry for the bad photo, I took it with my Laptop and I was trying not to touch it but it in a rather awkward position on the edge of a very steep bank. It is the first greenhood I have seen this season.

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: Photo shows the brown, notched labellum which distinguishes Pterostylis concinna from P. nana.

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: New species record for Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range. One clump of about 1m diameter.

items.title: Eucalyptus rubida
items.content_text: There are perhaps 100 trees like this in this large, open paddock, making it a very significant block of land. Unfortunately the block is a horse riding complex so plant variety in the understorey is limited.

items.title: Eucalyptus rubida
items.content_text: Edge of plains E. rubida distribution at plains-forest interface in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Paspalum distichum
items.content_text: Growing in the middle of the dried out Riddells Creek at Wybejong Park.

items.title: Gonocarpus humilis
items.content_text: One straggly plant on a dry creek. New species record for Conglomerate Gully and Riddells Creek.

items.title: Lonicera tatarica
items.content_text: Came up in in-laws' garden. It was 1.5m tall when we pulled it out. Could be first record in Australia.

items.title: Ehrharta erecta var. erecta
items.content_text: 2nd pic shows flowers. This is a serious weed. Taking over areas and easily spread by Council graders on dirt roads. Seed are enjoyed by seed-eating birds including finches and crimson rosellas.

items.title: Senecio microbasis
items.content_text: Last flowers of the season for this species. ID confirmed by Ian Thompson.

items.title: Vellereophyton dealbatum
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Elatine gratioloides, Limosella australis
items.content_text: Limosella australis is a new species record for Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range area. Unusual spathulate leaves. Wet edge of dam, hidden under a thicket of Eleocharis sphacelata. Elatine gratioloides in the background.

items.title: Trifolium fragiferum var. fragiferum
items.content_text: Growing alongside a dam.

items.title: Persicaria prostrata
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range area. Numerous plants at this dam, no plants at a nearby dam.

items.title: Conyza bonariensis
items.content_text: One plant on the side of an old dam. 5cm tall.

items.title: Linum trigynum
items.content_text: Many thousands of plants at this site. Mostly single-stemmed and upright but occasionally multi-stemmed and ascending stems on plants one foot wide. Flowers very small, same size as Cicendia and Sebaea.

items.title: Centrolepis aristata
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Lepidosperma curtisiae
items.content_text: Flower stem hidden deep within foliage. Very small plant well hidden among the grasses.

items.title: Anogramma leptophylla
items.content_text: Small annual fern growing on a sheltered rock ledge along creek.

items.title: Aphelia pumilio
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Montia fontana
items.content_text: ID to species by Neville Walsh. New species record for the Macedon Range. Growing in a trickle/seepage on rocks in an ephemeral part of the creek. Flowers tiny. Bifid style. Looks like a petal is missing but all flowers are like this - Levenhookia-like. Looks like 3 or 4 bilobed/notched petals.

items.title: Cicendia filiformis
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. Common in the two main open areas at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Levenhookia dubia
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range. Just one plant found near the base of the waterfall at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Linaria pelisseriana
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Centrolepis strigosa subsp. strigosa
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Hyacinthoides hispanica
items.content_text: Anthers bluer than depicted in photo. Flowers not or sub-secund. Plants growing around the garden, mostly in the lawn.

items.title: Myosotis discolor
items.content_text: A few plants in garden lawn.

items.title: Veronica arvensis
items.content_text: Growing in garden lawn.

items.title: Hydrocotyle callicarpa
items.content_text: Third photo of close-up of flowers by Russell Best

items.title: Gleichenia microphylla
items.content_text: New plant species record for Riddells Creek - species number 580.

items.title: Geitoneura klugii 'dark form', Pteridium esculentum
items.content_text: Using mostly Bracken as a territory lookout. If other butterfly species or males fly nearby they are quickly dispatched.

items.title: Cassytha pubescens s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for Mt Charlie Reserve. Only the second plant I've seen in the area (the other at Mt Teneriffe).

items.title: Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)
items.content_text: Confirmed ID from seed etc. About two dozen plants over 10x10m. No other populations of this species are known in Riddells Creek.
tags: id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)

items.title: Ornduffia reniformis
items.content_text: Also a male Austroagrion watsoni sitting on a leaf in pic2.

items.title: Mazus pumilio
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Calandrinia calyptrata
items.content_text: A few plants surviving in rock crevices.

items.title: Hydrocotyle sibthorpioides
items.content_text: 2m mat in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Frill of hairs at top of leaf stem (pic 3). Leaves glabrescent/shining above (only long fine hairs on upper surface) and some hairs visible on leaf under-surface. New species for Riddell.

items.title: Ranunculus glabrifolius
items.content_text: Fruit and leaf seem to confirm species. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Lotus subbiflorus
items.content_text: Very hairy. Umbel 3-flowered.

items.title: Eucalyptus globulus subsp. bicostata
items.content_text: This subspecies is defined by fruit in 3s and fruit sessile (stalkless). Small copse of young trees - not aware of any other populations in Riddells Creek. Possibly be a weed but hard to tell.

items.title: Amyema pendula subsp. pendula (s.s.)
items.content_text: Growing on Acacia dealbata. Also on A. mearnsii nearby. Grows on Eucs mostly in other areas of Riddells Creek.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: I think this might be A. buxifolia? Close to homes and bush so, if buxifolia, presumably an escapee. Not recorded other than NW Vic.

items.title: Acacia acinacea s.s.
items.content_text: The only remnant plants of this species known in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Acacia mucronata subsp. longifolia
items.content_text: Only a few plants known in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Acacia nanodealbata
items.content_text: One plant flowering on this walk. All others not flowering. In the days following many more plants have begun flowering nearby.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: Two plants within a few cm of each other, possibly joined by rhizome. None others noted but didn't have time to look closely. This fills a bit of a missing link in the species distribution. Again in its drier soil habitat.

items.title: Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata
items.content_text: Only one plant flowering on long walk. All other plants not flowering. Spindly small tree to 2m is typical in the Riddells Creek forest areas.

items.title: Eucalyptus ovata var. ovata
items.content_text: Mix of E. ovata and E. rubida at this location. Galls on the leaf.

items.title: Eucalyptus rubida
items.content_text: Candlebark with Melicytus dentatus s.s. at base. Fruit and buds a little unusual.

items.title: Senecio quadridentatus
items.content_text: Lake Park.

items.title: Einadia nutans
items.content_text: Lake Park.

items.title: Wahlenbergia luteola
items.content_text: Amazing anything remnant survives in Lake Park, but it does.

items.title: Wahlenbergia luteola
items.content_text: Lots flowering among a copse of Allocasuarina verticillata.

items.title: Cyathea australis
items.content_text: Only one plant seen at this location, on a Sandy Ck tributary. One Dicksonia antartica nearby too (8995).

items.title: Dicksonia antarctica
items.content_text: Only one plant seen at this location, on a Sandy Ck tributary. Another had died recently. This one's trunk in a deep hole. One Cyathea australis nearby too (8996).

items.title: Euchiton involucratus s.s.
items.content_text: Growing in rocks in the middle of the creek (Riddells Creek)

items.title: Mentha X piperita, Pieris rapae rapae
items.content_text: Leaves petiolate and 9cm x 3cm further down the stem.

items.title: Myriophyllum crispatum
items.content_text: Leaves terete in upper 90% of plant with a few lobed leaves at base. Leaves 6-whorled. Buds fusiform.

items.title: Elatine gratioloides
items.content_text: Seems to be a new species record for the Macedon Range. On the northern creekside at Wybejong Park.

items.title: Ozothamnus ferrugineus
items.content_text: First I've seen in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Dispar compacta, Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius
Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)
tags: id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)

items.title: Olearia glandulosa
items.content_text: Upright shrub, about 2.5m tall. Only one plant seen. Not formally recorded in Macedon Range since Ian Lunt's 1984 study. Probably locally very rare.

items.title: Geranium sp. 1
items.content_text: Almost white flowers but still a hint of pink. May not have been recorded in this section previously.

items.title: Gastrodia procera
items.content_text: New orchid species record for Riddells Creek. Tallest stem 80cm, perianth tube 20mm, 26 flowers on infloresence, stem is erect at the top when flowers are in bud.

items.title: Carex inversa
items.content_text: Spotted in the 'lawn'.

items.title: Amphibromus nervosus
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. Growing in a drying out Billabong.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. angustissimus
items.content_text: New plant for Riddells Creek. 1st pic shows upper leaves, 2nd shows distinctive mid-stem leaves.

items.title: Potamogeton cheesemanii
items.content_text: New record for Riddells Creek. What looks like a natural billabong with original flora pretty much intact.

items.title: Gladiolus cardinalis
items.content_text: A few plants in a (weedy) bush setting. One record on FIS and none at the Herbarium. Got to be a contender for 'prettiest weed'!

items.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.l.
items.content_text: Two populations found, adjacent but not overlapping (could be the same species) - see photos in this and the previous observation (differences in post-anther lobes and distribution of hairs in lateral lobes).

items.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.l.
items.content_text: Slender (not robust). Plants with probably a median of 4 flowers.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: T-Hill Reserve.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens (2)
items.content_text: Patch of about 10 plants. Only the second group of plants seen in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Caladenia moschata
items.content_text: Strong musky smell. 2-3 times taller than C. praecox and much later flowering.

items.title: Viola hederacea sensu Thiele & Prober
items.content_text: Purple in bud. All flowers fully open. Strong purple colour in flower centre. Relatively short peduncles. See 7479 for comparison with new species.

items.title: Viola spp.
items.content_text: White in bud. Only one flower 'open' (remainder 'closed' & nodding) on this warm day (flowers open more on hotter days). Light purple venation in flower centre. Relatively long peduncles. See 7480 for comparison with Viola hederacea.

items.title: Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) calophyllae, Pultenaea daphnoides
items.content_text: Native bee in remnant pea - no Apis mellifera in this plant, native bees only.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens
items.content_text:
Recently renamed as Acacia leprosa var. graveolens. This one is about 8m tall.
syn. Acacia verniciflua (southern variant)

items.title: Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa
items.content_text: Locally rare on the plains part of Riddells Creek (common in forested areas nearby). Plains plants are pretty much restricted to Rail Reserve where there is only one population I am aware of.

items.title: Leptorhynchos tenuifolius
items.content_text: Continued moisture seems to allow this species to retain flowers over a very long period, maybe all year.

items.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
items.content_text: Single old female plant surrounded by many young plants, all female. No male in this copse. The 'fruit' pictured are actually galls, probably Cylindrococcus (Hemiptera).

items.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
items.content_text: Male plant. This species is now locally rare owing to habitat destruction. The few remaining plants appear to be restricted to rail reserves (grassy plains woodland). Possibly no longer a viable remnant population?

items.title: Allocasuarina littoralis
items.content_text: Rare monoecious plant. Pic1 shows female (left) & male (bottom right) flowers on same plant. Pic2 = male plant left, monoecious plant right - latter has many female flowers & cones with a few male flowers on branchlet tips (all visible on pic3).

items.title: Solanum laciniatum, Strepera graculina
items.content_text: Ate 8-10 fruit. Initially seen perched in tree and thought it was a Grey Currawong (see pic 2). Pic 3 shows tail feather markings confirming it is the Pied Currawong. Probably moulting.

items.title: Wahlenbergia stricta subsp. stricta
items.content_text: Showing campanulate (bell-shaped) flower tube.

items.title: Conium maculatum
items.content_text: A declared noxious weed.

items.title: Prunella vulgaris
items.content_text: In a swampy area.

items.title: Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa, Scaptia auriflua
items.content_text: Feeding in Bursaria spinosa.

items.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
items.content_text: Keys out best as A.sp.3 but some features of fimbriatum too. fimbriatum because of purple anthers and appendages, unbranched stem, leaves not distantly ciliate (it has distant teeth). sp.3 features - erect fruiting pedicels, leaves present at flowering.

items.title: Sambucus gaudichaudiana
items.content_text: Not previously recorded in Riddells Creek. Growing on the edge of Charlies Creek.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. omnigracilis
items.content_text: omnigracilis means all bits (onmi) slender (gracilis) - referring to leaf and leaf lobes, all of which are slender.

items.title: Calochilus robertsonii
items.content_text: Purplish Beard Orchid.

items.title: Diuris sulphurea
items.content_text: Diuris sulphurea, Tiger Orchid.

items.title: Coprosma quadrifida
items.content_text: First record of this species for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Hypochaeris radicata, Trapezites lutea lutea
items.content_text: First lutea of the season although I haven't had chance to look much before this date.

items.title: Carex breviculmis
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm. It has come up in an area where gorse was removed two years ago.

items.title: Schoenus apogon
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm. Thousands have come up after the rain over the past two seasons.

items.title: Centrolepis strigosa subsp. strigosa
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range (one record on FIS at Woodend Racecourse). Came up after clearing a large patch of gorse 2 years ago.

items.title: Cassytha pubescens s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range (no previous records on FIS or other accessible databases). Plants only seen on the wetter side and on the very top (plateau). None noted on the drier, northern slopes. Spotted by Chris Lindorff. Location approxima

items.title: Dianella amoena
items.content_text: Location approximate - to within 20m.

items.title: Platylobium obtusangulum
items.content_text: Previously unrecorded in the Macedon Ranges

items.title: Acacia falciformis
items.content_text: A few plants found by David Francis. This one is about 100km away from its previously known distribution.

items.title: Eucalyptus viminalis subsp. viminalis
items.content_text: Very old/large Manna Gum opposite 410 Gap Road, Riddells Creek. Large hollow is currently home to nesting Kookaburras. Full of life with Koalas, 2 x possum species and many other birds, animals and insects seen in and around it.

items.title: Isolepis prolifera
items.content_text: In an inundated part of track.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: Dipodium roseum with D. pardalinum in the background.

items.title: Eucalyptus obliqua
items.content_text: This is about the lowest remnant down towards the bottom of Gap Road.

items.title: Eucalyptus obliqua
items.content_text: Coming to the end of its flowering. Strong, sweet smell when close to flowers.

items.title: 595 ids
items.content_text: Species list for collection.

id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)

items.title: Acianthus pusillus
items.content_text:
Species information: Orchid, 4 - 18 cm tall. Single leaf cordate, flat-to-ground, reddish-purple beneath.
Flowers 118, translucent green or pinkish with reddish veins and spots.
Flowers Apr - Aug.

items.title: Senecio pinnatifolius var. lanceolatus, Syrphidae spp.
